helpContent@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netduma:
Ping shows the connection quality (the ping) from you to the connection you have selected on the map. It is measured in milliseconds ('ms'). If Auto-Ping is enabled in your Geo-Filter Map then the ping shown is the ping from you to the host / server of your game.

Host Tick Rate measures the amount of packets sent per second from the host of your game, usually a server, to you. The higher, the better.

Client Tick Rate measures the amount of packets per second you are sending to the host of your game.

Send Rate measures the amount of data sent per second from the host of your game, usually a server, to you.

Receive Rate measures the amount of data per second you are sending to the host of your game.

Connection Benchmark tests three factors of your internet connection and grades it against your predefined network speeds. Press Run Test to begin. You can then watch as the test is carried out. Results from the test are saved in the History section below.

splashContent@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netdu:
Traffic controller lets you set rules for specific devices and traffic, allowing for flexible and scheduled blocking and freezing of Internet access. With traffic controller, traffic can be blocked based on application, device or port in accordance to your schedule.

For example, parents can use traffic controller to easily block all traffic for their children's devices, or specifically block gaming and streaming on the computer when it's homework time. For smart homes, you can close Internet access to your unused ports to ensure your home keeps unwanted intrusion at bay.

The Traffic Rules panel allows you to add and view all of your rules, as well as details of when they apply. The Event Capture panel provides details on when rules have become active and blocked traffic.

helpContent@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netduma:
VPN Traffic is used to select the devices and services you want to apply your VPN to. Before applying any rules, make sure you have successfully setup your VPN. See the VPN Setup panel to do this.

Once you have successfully logged into your VPN provider on your router, click Add Device and select the device you want to apply your VPN to. After adding a device, the entire device will be in the VPN. But if you just want to apply the VPN to a specific service, you can select from one of the following modes:

  • Do not VPN these services will apply the VPN to every service on your device except the services you choose. For example, you could apply the VPN to your PC but exclude a game like League of Legends from the VPN.
  • Only VPN these services will only apply the VPN to the services you select. For example, you could apply the VPN to Skype on your PC, but all other applications on your PC will not be sent through the VPN.

With the VPN mode selected, select the services you wish to either exclude or include in your VPN. Click the Add Service button to bring up a pre-set list of popular services. Click Advanced if you wish to manually add a port rule instead.

When selected, Always applies Congestion Control at all times, so you can play games with less chance of a greedy device or application causing you to lag. Your total bandwidth speeds are reduced, so remember to select Never when you have finished gaming.

Auto-Enable only applies Congestion Control when games are being played (all console games and most computer games are automatically detected by DumaOS). Your total bandwidth speeds will only be reduced when gaming is detected.

Never disables Congestion Control. You receive your full bandwidth speeds, but if all your bandwidth is being used, your games are caught in a queue, causing lag.

helpContent@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netduma:
A virtual private network ('VPN') is used to mask your real IP addresses from the Internet. When a VPN connection is made, the VPN server replaces your real IP address with an IP address from the VPN server, keeping your home Internet connection secure.

Hybrid VPN offers far more control than a regular router VPN. Instead of applying your VPN to your entire network, you can choose the individual devices you would like the VPN to be applied to. For example, your console, your PC, and/or your phone. You can also choose specific services you then want in the VPN. For example, you could choose to just apply your VPN to Skype on your PC, or a specific port range.

This means you can protect the devices or services that need it, without forcing the rest of your network to go through a VPN which is usually slower than a normal connection.

To setup a VPN on your router, click on VPN Setup. You need an active subscription to a VPN provider so you will be asked to enter your VPN provider details. If you do not have a provider, there are many options available if you look online.

You can either choose a VPN provider from the preset list found in Basic setup, or you can use the Advanced setup and input your VPN provider's OpenVPN config file (most VPN providers can give you this).

Once you have successfully logged into your VPN provider on your router you then need to choose how you would like the VPN to be applied. See the VPN Traffic panel for next steps.

Block Traffic If VPN Disconnects will disable your Internet connection if your VPN is disconnected. If you check this box, then you will not be able to access the Internet if your VPN goes down. We only recommend checking this box if you are extra sensitive about your security.

welcomeIntro@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netdum:
QoS is a Router App dedicated to giving you power over which parts of your internet traffic matter most. The QoS feature is split into two sections that work together: Congestion Control and Bandwidth Allocation.

Congestion Control limits the amount of bandwidth non-gaming traffic can use while you game, reducing queueing and avoiding lag. We recommend setting each slider at 70% as a starting point, and then tweaking the sliders to perfect Congestion Control for your connection.

Meanwhile, bandwidth allocation allows you to share your bandwidth out according to the activities you use most, such as gaming, messaging, livestreaming, and media. All you need to do is adjust sliders to match what you use most. Alternatively, you can share your bandwidth between your devices instead of your traffic.

Press ADD RULE to begin using the feature. Choose Block to prevent connections, and choose Allow to override your Blocks.

goodputEnabledInformation@/dumaos/apps/u: Each packet has a header usually about 40 - 60 bytes out of 1500 bytes. Goodput means assign extra bandwidth to accommodate the headers so your bandwidth is closer to the speedtest result.
helpContentTwo@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netd:
Ping assist enhances your geo-filter by allowing servers or players are located outside your geo-filter range to connect to you if they have a low ping.

For example, if only servers in the UK were allowed by your settings, but a server in Germany tried to connect to you, ping assist allows the connection if it has a ping value less than your ping assist number.

We recommend you set your ping assist value between 30 ms and 50 ms to begin with. Any connection below that number is allowed to connect to you. You can then increase or decrease this value based on your personal preference.

To disable ping assist, set the value to 0 ms.

Flush Cloud reloads the geo-filter's IP list. It is only necessary to select this option if you were advised to by Technical Support.
